def display(n: dict[int, pd.DataFrame], kind: str = "plot", title: str = "", unit: str = ""):
    df = []
    for k, ni in n.items():
        df.append(ni.sum(axis=1).rename(f"{k}"))
    df = pd.concat(df, axis=1)
    if kind == "plot":
        df.sort_index().fillna(method="ffill").plot(title=title, ylabel=unit)
    elif kind == "bar":
        df.plot.bar(title=title, ylabel=unit)
    elif kind == "hist":
        df.plot.hist(title=title, xlabel=unit, alpha=0.8)
    else:
        raise RuntimeError

def get_state_of_charge_t(n, carrier):
    df = n.storage_units_t.state_of_charge.T.reset_index()
    df = df.merge(n.storage_units.reset_index()[["carrier", "StorageUnit"]], on="StorageUnit")
    df = df.groupby(by="carrier").sum()
    del df["StorageUnit"]
    return df.T[[carrier]]

Overview of performances¶

Performances are evaluated on the following hypothesis :

  • All EU countries
  • 37 clusters
  • Optimizing only electricity
  • 1 year (2013)
  • Planning horizons : 2050
  • Myopic run
  • Allowed line transmission volume expansion : 1.1

Check influence of aggregation¶

  • Aggregation works as low pass filter on timeseries.
  • Reducing aggregation time increases the visibility of daily patterns.
  • Nominal power generation and store capaicty is influenced by those hypothesis.
In [ ]:
agg = [96, 72, 48, 24] #, 12, 3]

n_h = {}
for a in agg:
    n_h[f"{a}H"] = pypsa.Network(Path(n_path, n_name + f"{a}H_2050.nc"))

display({k: ni.loads_t["p"] for k, ni in n_h.items()}, title = "Active power load for various aggregations", unit = "MW")

    display({k: get_state_of_charge_t(ni, carrier) for k, ni in n_h.items()}, title=f"State of charge of {carrier} for various aggregations", unit="MWh")

Check influence of segmentation¶

  • Segmentation seems keep more peak in the load.
  • Increasing the number of segments increases the visibility of those peaks
  • Nominal power generation and store capaicty is influenced by those hypothesis.

Compare time aggregation and segmentation¶

  • Aggregation shows clear daily patterns.
  • Segmentation shows loads peaks.
